'''''Palaemon serratus''''', also called the '''common prawn''', is a [[species]] of [[shrimp]] found in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] from [[Denmark]] to [[Mauritania]], and in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] and [[Black Sea]]&nbsp;<ref name="ARKive">{{cite web |url=http://www.arkive.org/common-prawn/palaemon-serratus/info.html |title=Common prawn (''Palaemon serratus'') |publisher=[[ARKive]] |accessdate=2009-01-31}}</ref>.

==Ecology==
Individuals live for 3<U+2013>5 years&nbsp;<ref name="Torry"/> in groups of about 40 in rocky crevices at depths of up to 40&nbsp;m&nbsp;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mida.ucc.ie/pages/atlas/atlas.php?theme=Fisheries/Aquaculture |title=Marine Irish Digital Atlas |accessdate=2009-01-31 |publisher=[[University College Cork]]}}</ref>. Females grow faster than males, and the population is highly seasonal, with a pronounced peak in the autumn&nbsp;<ref>{{cite journal |title=Population characteristics of the prawn ''Palaemon serratus'' (Decapoda, Palaemonidae) in a shallow Mediterranean bay |author=Guillermo Guerao & Carlos Ribera |journal=[[Crustaceana]] |volume=73 |issue=4 |pages=459<U+2013>468 |doi=10.1163/156854000504543 |url=http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/brill/cr/2000/00000073/00000004/art00008 |year=2000}}</ref>. They are preyed upon by a variety of [[fish]], including species of [[Mullidae]], [[Moronidae]], [[Sparidae]] and [[Batrachoididae]]&nbsp;<ref>{{cite journal |title=Feeding ecology and trophic relationships of fish species in the lower Guadiana River Estuary and Castro Marim e Vila Real de Santo Ant<U+00F3>nio salt marsh |author=Rita S<U+00E1>, Constan<U+00E7>a Bexigaa, Pedro Veigaa, Lina Vieiraa & Karim Erzini |doi=10.1016/j.ecss.2006.05.038 |url= |journal=[[Estuarine, Coastal and Shelf Science]] |volume=70 |issue=1-2 |year=2006 |pages=19<U+2013>26}}</ref>.

==Description==
''P. serratus'' may be distinguished from other species of shrimp by the [[Rostrum (anatomy)|rostrum]], which curves upwards, is bifurcated at the tip and has 6<U+2013>7 along its upper edge, and 4<U+2013>5 teeth on the lower edge&nbsp;<ref name="ARKive"/>. Other speciesmay have a slightly curved rostrum, but then the teeth on its dorsal surface continue into the distal third, which is untoothed in ''P. serratus''&nbsp;<ref>{{cite journal |title=First records of the oriental prawn ''Palaemon macrodactylus'' (Decapoda: Caridea), an alien species in European waters, with a revised key to British Palaemonidae |author=Christopher W. Ashelby, Tim M. Worsfold & Charles H. J. M. Fransen |journal=[[Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom]] |year=2004 |volume=84 |pages=1041<U+2013>1050 |url=http://decapoda.nhm.org/pdfs/24611/24611.pdf |doi=10.1017/S0025315404010392h}}</ref>. ''P. serratus'' is pinkish brown, with reddish patterns, and is typically 100&nbsp;mm in length, making it the largest of the native shrimps and [[prawn]]s around the [[British Isles]]&nbsp;<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.fao.org/docrep/005/ac741t/AC741T34.htm |title=The suitability of the English prawn ''Palaemon serratus'' (Pennant) for cultivation <U+2014> a preliminary assessment |publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization]] |journal=FAO Fisheries Report |volume=R57 |issue=3 |year=1968 |pages=582 pp. |author=M. R. Reeve}}</ref>.

''P. serratus'' is one of the few [[invertebrate]]s to have its hearing studied in detail; it is sensitive to [[frequency|frequencies]] between 100&nbsp;Hz and 3kHz, with an [[acuity]] similar to that of generalist [[fish]]&nbsp;<ref>{{cite journal |title=The hearing abilities of the prawn ''Palaemon serratus'' |author=J. M. Lovella, M. M. Findlaya, R. M. Moateb & H. Y. Yan |year=2005 |journal=[[Comparative Biochemistry and Physiology]], Part A |volume=140 |pages=89<U+2013>100 |doi=10.1016/j.cbpb.2004.11.003}}</ref>. While the hearing range of a ''P. serrratus'' individual changes as it grows, all are capable of hearing tones at 500&nbsp;Hz&nbsp;<ref>{{cite journal |journal=[[Journal of Experimental Biology]] |volume=209 |pages=2480<U+2013>2485 |year=2006 |doi=10.1242/jeb.02211|title=The relationship between body size and evoked potentials from the statocysts of the prawn ''Palaemon serratus'' |author=J. M. Lovell, R. M. Moate, L. Christiansen & M. M. Findlay |url=http://jeb.biologists.org/cgi/content/full/209/13/2480}}</ref>.

==Fisheries==
A small [[Shrimp fishery|commercial fishery]] exists for ''P. serratus'' on the west coast of [[Great Britain]]&nbsp;<ref name="Torry">{{cite web |url=http://www.fao.org/wairdocs/tan/x5931e/x5931e01.htm |title=Handling and processing shrimp |author=Torry Research Station |work=Torry Advisory Notes <U+2014> No. 54 |publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization]]}}</ref>, chiefly in [[West Wales]] ([[Cemaes Head]] to the [[Ll<U+0177>n Peninsula]]&nbsp;<ref name="Percy">{{cite web |url=http://www.nwnwsfc.org/archive/scibye_mins/scibye20apr07/percy_prawn_paper.htm |author=Jeremy Percy |year=2006 |title=The Welsh coastal ''Palaemon'' prawn fisheries <U+2014> a consideration of future possible actions |publisher=[[North Western & North Wales Sea Fisheries Committee]]}}</ref>), but extending increasingly far north to include parts of [[Scotland]]&nbsp;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seafish.org/b2b/info.asp?p=109 |title=''Palaemon serratus'': sustainable development |publisher=[[Sea Fish Industry Authority|Seafish]] |accessdate=2009-01-31}}</ref>. In [[Ireland]], fishing for ''P. serratus'' began at [[Baltimore, County Cork]] in the 1970s and subsequently expanded. A peak landing of 548&nbsp;t was recorded in 1999, and four [[counties of Ireland|counties]] account for over 90% of the catch <U+2014> [[Galway]], [[County Kerry|Kerry]], [[County Cork|Cork]] and [[County Waterford|Waterford]]&nbsp;<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.bioone.org/doi/full/10.2983/0730-8000(2006)25%5B1021%3AIOPITF%5D2.0.CO%3B2 |title=Indicators of performance in the fishery for shrimp ''Palaemon serratus'' (Pennant) in Irish Coastal Waters |journal=[[Journal of Shellfish Research]] |year=2006 |author=Edward Fahy, Niamh Forrest, Ruth Mortimer & Jim Carroll |volume=25 |issue=3 |pages=1021<U+2013>1026 |doi=10.2983/0730-8000(2006)25[1021:IOPITF]2.0.CO;2 |doi_brokendate=2010-03-17}}</ref>. There is now concern that the current levels of exploitation may represent [[overfishing]], and measures are being considered to limit the catch, such as a [[minimum landing size]]&nbsp;<ref name="Percy"/>.

